      • getReturnedNode

        public Value getReturnedNode()
        Get the Value that returns a value if it is used in an expression.

        For example: 
         // Scenario 1
 tree.value.next;
 
 //Scenario 2
 tree;
        In scenario 1, "next" is the returned node because it is the last accessed node. In scenario 2 "tree" is the returned node because it does not access any nodes and is therefore the value that is returned.
        Overrides:
        getReturnedNode in class Value
        Returns:
        The last accessed node, or if the node does not access any nodes, it returns itself.

      • setName

        public void setName(java.lang.String name)
        Set the name of the Identifier. Identifier names consist of the following character types: [A-Z, a-z, 0-9, _]. However, cannot start with a number.

        Example inputs include:
        • correctGrammar
        • INCORrect_grammaR_but_123123STILL_workz
        • identifierName4

        Incorrect inputs include:
        • 24JeffGordon (Cannot start an identifier with a number)
        • This.Doesnt_work (Cannot contain a period (or any other punctuation))
        • #omgProgramin (This is not Twitter)
        Parameters:
        name - The String containing the name to set as the identifier.

      • getReferenceNode

        public Identifier getReferenceNode()
        Get the Node that represents the value that contains the value.
        For example:
         ClassName obj = new ClassName();
 
 obj.data.methodName();
        In the previous statements, the method "methodName()" is being referenced through the "data" identifier.

        If the identifier is not explicitly called through an object, it will return the instance type that the node was referenced within.
        For example: 
         obj.calculateArea().width;
        The Identifier for the method call "calculateArea()" is returned.

        If the node is referenced within a static context, the containing ClassDeclaration is returned.
        For example: 
         Time.currentTimeMillis();
        The Identifier for the ClassDeclaration "Time" is returned.
        Returns:
        The Node that represents the calling Identifier.

      • getContextNode

        public Identifier getContextNode()
        Get the furthest node that is accessing the specified identifier.

        For example: 
         tree.next.calculateSize()
        In the previous statement, "tree" is the context. If the identifier is not accessed by any other identifiers, then null is returned.
        For example: 
         calculateSize()
        The above would return null.
        Returns:
        The furthest node that accesses the specified identifier.

      • getRootAccessNode

        public Identifier getRootAccessNode()
        Get the furthest node that is accessing the specified identifier.

        For example: 
         tree.next.calculateSize()
        In the previous statement, "tree" is the context. This differs from the getContextNode() call by returning the specified node if the identifier is not accessed by any other identifiers.
        For example: 
         calculateSize()
        The above would return the method call identifier for "calculateSize()".
        Returns:
        The furthest node that accesses the specified identifier.

        public Identifier getRootNode()

        Returns:
        The root Node that accesses the specified Identifier.

      • generateCUseOutput

        public java.lang.StringBuilder generateCUseOutput(java.lang.StringBuilder builder)
        Generate the representation of when the variable is being used, in action, rather than being declared.

        For example:
         Person p;
 p.getName();
        The first line shows the declaration of the Variable. The second line demonstrates a "variable use" for the "p" variable. Essentially, the "variable use" output is exactly what it says, what the variable looks like when it is being used to do something.
        Overrides:
        generateCUseOutput in class Value
        Returns:
        What the variable looks like when it is being used to do something.
